<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Lessons of the Affirmative Action Campaign</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<center>

<H1>Lessons of the Affirmative Action Campaign</H1>
<H2>A Look at the Future From California</H2>
<p>
  <H3>By Larry P. Arnn</H3>

</center>

As usual, the eccentricities of California, both good and bad, open a window on the future of the whole nation.  We entered the election holding our breath, took a beating, and came out glad it wasn't worse. Conservative losses were more severe here than in most places, but on the other hand they were offset by a grand, potentially decisive victory. 
<p>
That victory is the heavily debated Proposition 209, the California Civil Rights Initiative. Prop. 209 passed 54% to 46%. It ran sixteen points ahead of Bob Dole, who broadcast about $2 million worth of advertisements in its favor in the last ten days. It ran 3 points ahead of Bill Clinton, who opposed it throughout the campaign, actively at the end when his own victory was certain. The opposition campaign spent about as much as all proponents together, excluding the amount the CCRI campaign spent gathering signatures, mostly in 1995. 
<p>
The initiative was therefore very strong. Read its operative language to the voters today in any state, and more than 60% of them will support it. A good campaign on its behalf by the Republican Party would have helped them substantially in California even in this bad year.
<p>
The battle was at the end as stormy as its subject matter foretold. The opposition finally got some support from the president both in fundraising and in public statements. They used the money to show advertisements featuring David Duke, side by side with Newt Gingrich, as the key supporter of 209. Of course a cross burned brightly against a deep night in the background. In another ad, a male hand stripped a uniform off a police woman while a voice said, "take it off, take it all off." David Duke had in fact been invited into the state to speak for 209 by--naturally--the opposition, personified in this case by Blenda Wilson, administrator at California state university Northridge, who paid Duke $4,000 to come.
<p> 
This ranting was neither unexpected nor effective. Alas, the Republican campaign in favor of 209 was also crude, and much less heart felt, than these opposition ravings. In this failure is found the clearest lesson for the future. That lesson is easy to understand, and with a little virtue of the kind that statesmen must possess, easy to implement. 
<p> 
The lesson is clear from the history. The California Civil Rights initiative was conceived in 1992-93 by Glynn Custred and Tom Wood, who were driven by a commitment of principle, which led them to a brilliant practical insight. Their work began to get national press attention in late 1993-94; by early 1995 it was a highly celebrated cause. Polls showed right away that the language of the initiative was popular. This was no surprise, as race and gender preferences have never been liked by ordinary people.
<p>
In early 1995, Wood and Custred began the hard job of making the initiative happen. They recruited help, among those who came along was Arnie Steinberg, myself, and eventually Ward Connerly, who would carry heavy burdens very far. Gradually an excellent team was assembled.
<p>
It should be noted that these people favored the initiative for its own sake. They did not think it their job to make it a partisan matter. They sought to place it first upon the March 1996 primary ballot, which would give maximum possibility for bi-partisan support. They sought to make a coalition with the Democratic Leadership Council in California. They knew, of course, that Democrats would mostly oppose the initiative. They knew that the Democratic Party is deeply invested in the preferences and quotas that Proposition 209 will eliminate wherever it reaches. Therefore the Republican opportunity would be there, if the Republican Party were able to seize it. 
<p>
By the second quarter of 1995, CCRI was a national issue. In July 1995 President Clinton made a major address endorsing affirmative action: "mend it, don't end it." The following week Senator Dole put his name on a bill written in the House by Florida Congressman Charles Canady and his committee staffer William McGrath. Dole had called Canady to ask to be co-sponsor of the bill. Canady, who hoped to put that bill on the desk of Bill Clinton within a year, could not refuse the Senate majority leader. Dole thereby stole a march on Phil Gramm. He had the advantage and the power to use it to produce legislation, at least in the Senate. He could make the bill move. Would he? 
<p>
He did not. In both the House and the Senate, the Dole-Canady Equal Opportunity Act was trapped in committee, and despite gallant efforts it never got out. Together with welfare and partial birth abortion (another Canady initiative), it could have formed the core of a national debate reaching to the fundamental differences between the parties. 
<p>
The Republicans in Congress needed this debate, even if they were not ready for it.  Our Constitution is not so arranged as to permit one branch of government to alter major policy by itself. The obvious conclusion is that Republicans, if they are in fact the party of change, must seek to control both houses of Congress and the presidency. The urgent work therefore is not partial solutions in Medicare. The urgent work is to demonstrate to the people where they differ in principle, upon central matters, from the president. If these differences are clear, then the people will be able to make an informed choice the next time they get to vote. This strategy was not followed generally, and it was not followed in particular upon civil rights.
<p>
Bill Clinton was ready. In his July 1995 speech he gave a ringing endorsement of "affirmative action," the useful term that means either outreach or preferences, depending upon the hearer and the speaker.  Consider these finely crafted phrases from the president:
<p>
<blockquote><I>Let me be clear about what affirmative action must not mean and what I won't allow it to be. It does not mean--and I don't favor--the unjustified preference of the unqualified over the qualified of any race or gender. It doesn't mean--and I don't favor--numerical quotas. It doesn't mean - and I don't favor -- rejection or selection of any employee or student solely on the basis of race or gender without regard to merit.</I></blockquote>
<p>
With these words the president sets his limits upon race and sex preferences in government action. The first sentence means that favoring the unqualified over the qualified on account of race and sex can be justified. The second sentence means "quotas" that are not "numerical" are fine. The third means that race and sex can be a factor, even the main or overwhelming factor, even when they have nothing to do with the matter at hand, so long as they are not the "only" factor. 
<p>
President Clinton was then passionate and strong--and utterly equivocal. The surest way to clear up the equivocation was to present him with a bill and force him to sign it or veto it. That opportunity was lost by the inaction of the Congress, led of course by Senator/candidate Bob Dole.
<p>
Back in California, the CCRI struggled to qualify. Speaker Gingrich, resisted by his staff, did good anyway by signing a fundraising letter on its behalf.  Finally the resources of all the key participants came together to get the initiative qualified.  Ward Connerly, generous Californians such as Darrel Issa, Dusty Rhodes from New York and others across the country, joined the campaign team and the Republican Party to make qualification and a vigorous campaign possible.
<p>
But the party and Dole treated the initiative in just the same way that they treated the Dole-Canady bill in Congress. They made sure it was there, as a place holder. But they made no commitment to argue for it. 
Candidate Dole endorsed CCRI in late March 96. Shortly thereafter he published an article in its favor in the <I>Los Angeles Times</I>. Then. . .nothing. The press began to notice that preferences had no place in Dole speeches. His California strategist, Ken Kachigian, stated at a press conference that the campaign might have little to do with the issue. On June 20, the <I>Times</I> wrote a front page story about Dole's moving away from it. This continued through the summer until past the convention, at which Connerly was not allowed to speak.  The accession of Kemp to the ticket brought his endorsement, but thereafter Dole was almost silent and Kemp was equivocal.
<p>
Throughout this long period, the Dole campaign had little money that it could spend legally on its own behalf. It tore its hair out trying to generate favorable media to offset the large advertising budgets of Clinton and his union friends. It failed, partly because the candidate had little to say. 
<p>
Dole might have spent the summer bringing up case after case of preferences.  He could have started with the wonderful case of Cheryl Hopwood in Texas, in which an appellate court ruled that the University of Texas had excluded her from law school admission because of her color. The Clinton Administration appealed the case, to attempt to get the Supreme Court to rule that race and gender preferences are lawful. Thus he took a plain and open position. Dole said nothing. 
<p>
The Hopwood case illustrates what is in fact happening in public bureaucracies all over America. In truth and in demonstrated fact, the government systematically categorizes and selects--and also necessarily excludes--on the basis of race and gender. It also hides what it does. When it is found out, its officials often lie. When they are confronted, they employ intimidation, then bribery, then finally compromise covered by the assertion that this particular case is an anomaly.  This is the behavior revealed in case after case arising when a stubborn and tough person sues against the system of official preference. This is the pattern of behavior that is proved by these cases to be common in government bodies in every part of the country. 
<p>
The pattern of action does not occur by any accident. Race preference today is a government practice built upon the idea that human beings are clay, molded by past experience into distorted shapes, needing some shaping up by government to put them right.  It is a despotic idea. It makes us objects to be acted upon. It destroys the idea of the citizen, inviolable in his rights, to be governed only by consent. It makes the officials of the government sovereign.
<p>
Dole might have spent some time, then, arguing in favor of his own position, which God bless him for having, but about which he was mute.  He might even have used his massive power to raise funds to help CCRI put up its own advertisements, which were made to argue the case on the highest ground. All of these steps would have won him news.  They would have shown voters he was serious about the issue.  They would have established an argument that he could pursue in the debates and during the heat of the campaign. 
<p>
Dole and the Republican Party squandered these months, which were rich with opportunity. The consequences were fatal. Having no strategy in Congress except to stall, no strategy in the public debate except to duck, they were driven at the end to film television spots with ten days to go. The work was ham fisted and had to be redone at least twice. The people of California had every right to think that this fundamental issue was being used out of desperation as a tool of low politics. 
<p>
We can draw a lesson from the election in California. In a bad year, when an able president of the left ran a splendid campaign to the right and got away with it, an issue of high principle was fought and won. This issue does not appear to the voters primarily as a question of money or interest. It raises in simple form the question what is government for, and what is the standing of the citizen before it. It has proved more useful than all the clever stunts and strategems, all the polls and focus groups that millions can purchase. 
<p>
 We should continue this debate. We should advance it in the Congress and in every state. We should not think of it or speak of it as a wedge issue, but rather as a matter of right and justice. We should build a great political movement upon this plain idea that we are equal before the law, that government is limited, and that the rights of all are to be protected by it equally. 
<p>
Finally, we should search until we find politicans who can speak up for it. The art of statesmanship is the application of principle to policy. Here is a chance to practice that art, difficult but decisively rewarding. 
<p>
<I>Larry P. Arnn is President of the Claremont Institute, and initially Chairman, then Chairman of the National Advisory Council, of Proposition 209.</I>

<P>

<a href="victim.html">Equal Opportunities Denied</a><br> <i>by Tom McClintock and Steven McCarthy</i><p>
<a href="citguide.html">A Citizen's Guide to the Affirmative Action</a><br> <i>by Douglas A. Jeffrey and Brian T. Kennedy</i><p>
<a href="fairness.html">America's Passion for Fairness</a><br> <i>by Larry P. Arnn</i><p>
<a href="trainwrk.html">The Affirmative Action Trainwreck</a><br> <i>by Edward J. Erler</i><p>

