<!---------------------------------------------------------------->


<HR  width=50%>
<H1>Tax, Spend - and Elect?

</H1>
<p>

<p>
<H3>ALAN REYNOLDS
</H3>  
<P>
<HR  width=50>Mr. Reynolds is director of economic research at the Hudson Institute. He also served as research director to Jack Kemp's National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform.




<BR>
<HR  width=50%>
</CENTER>
<P>



<FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT><font size=+1>N 1992</font>, the economy grew by 2.7 per cent. Candidate Bill Clinton described that as ``the worst economic performance in fifty years.'' In 1995 the economy grew by around 2 per cent. Yet in this January's State of the Union message, the President said the economy is ``the healthiest in thirty years.'' So on which, if either, occasion was Bill Clinton telling the truth?
<P>
By every conceivable measure of income, output, or productivity, the economy has performed poorly on Clinton's watch, particularly in comparison with what Bob Bartley dubbed ``the seven fat years'' of 1983 to 1989.
<P>
<b>Gross domestic product:</b> Real GDP, the most comprehensive measure of the economy's output, grew by only 2.3 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, down from 3.9 per cent in 1983 - 89.
<P>
<b>Productivity:</b> Growth of output per hour in the non-farm business sector averaged only 0.5 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, down from 1.6 per cent in 1983 - 89. Labor Department figures on ``multifactor productivity'' show the ratio of capital to labor falling in 1993 - 94, which inevitably slows the growth of productivity, real wages, and family incomes.
<P>
<b>Real disposable income:</b> After-tax personal income rose by only 2.3 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, down from 3.5 per cent in 1983 - 89.
Real labor compensation: Real hourly wages and benefits rose by 7 per cent in 1981 - 88, but were virtually flat from 1988 to 1995.
<P>
<b>Employment:</b> As measured by the household survey, employment grew by only 1.9 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, down from 2.4 per cent in 1983 - 89. Measured by an alternative survey of business (which may count the same workers twice), payroll employment grew by 2.6 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, but that too was down from 3 per cent in 1983 - 89.
<P>
<b>Labor force:</b> The supply of new workers slowed to 0.8 per cent a year in 1993 - 95, down from 1.8 per cent in 1983 - 89. Demographics can't begin to explain this huge and sudden drop in the willingness to look for work, but disincentives in our tax and transfer payments can.
<P>
<b>Savings:</b> Gross private savings amounted to only 14.6 per cent of GDP in 1993 - 95, down from 17.2 per cent in 1983 - 89.
<P>
Was this trip really necessary?
<P>
Even in the very few areas where the economy appears to have fared relatively well, it still fails to measure up to the lofty standards set by the Reagan years. The Clinton Administration points with pride to growth of real exports, which did indeed rise at an 8.3 per cent rate over the past three years. But imports grew faster -- at a 10 per cent rate. In 1983 - 89, by contrast, real exports grew by 9.4 per cent a year, and imports by 8.6 per cent.
<P>
One statistic almost summarizes all the rest: Median family income fell by more than 5 per cent from 1989 through 1994 (the latest available figure). By contrast, median family income rose by 12.6 per cent from 1982 to 1989. These figures are before taxes, so they understate the actual drop in living standards following the 1993 increase in taxes on incomes, Social Security benefits and gasoline.
<P>
Income statistics for 1995 and 1996 are unlikely to look much better. Real wages were flat in 1995, and employment nearly so (by January 1996, employment was only 0.4 per cent higher than a year earlier). Wages picked up a bit in early 1996, but so did inflation. The increase in consumer prices averaged 3.6 per cent in the first half of this year, wiping out nominal wage increases in the process. Recent employment gains have slowed to 1.5 per cent or less, compared with the same month a year ago.
<P>
Because employment grew at about the same slow 2 per cent pace as the economy in the past three years, it follows that output per worker (productivity) must have grown very slowly. Indeed, productivity growth averaged only 0.6 per cent in 1993 - 95, down from 1.6 in 1983 - 89. There is no mystery at all about why real wages have stagnated in the past three years, despite a flood of misinformed news reports on that topic. Real output per worker and real income per worker are just two different ways of looking at the same thing. If we don't produce more, there won't be more to go around.
<P>
The Clinton Administration would much prefer to reduce all these uncomfortable economic comparisons to a single statement -- namely, the claim that the President himself has personally ``created'' nearly ten million jobs. The reason for that single-minded focus is obvious: ten million new jobs sounds like an impressive number. In fact, it isn't. If employment had grown as rapidly in 1993 - 95 as it did in 1983 - 89, the economy would have generated two million <I>more</I> jobs than it did between the end of 1992 and 1995.
<P>
There are two ways the unemployment rate can go down. One is for employers to offer more jobs. The other is for fewer people to go looking for jobs (to be listed as unemployed you must be looking for a job and not finding one). As it happens, surprisingly few people have been looking for work. Growth in the labor force has slowed to a crawl. This puts severe limits on future employment growth, and therefore on economic growth as well. And it is one link, but only one, between the decidedly mediocre growth of output and income and the 1993 increase in marginal tax rates.
<P>
The 1996 Economic Report of the President complains, ``some claimed these tax rate increases [e.g., in 1993] would do severe harm to the economy by creating disincentives for individuals to work and save. Again, these forecasts turned out to be false, just as did the earlier supply-side forecasts of rapid growth from tax reductions.'' It is difficult to imagine what numbers the President's economists have been looking at. If 3.9 per cent economic growth from 1983 to 1989 did not constitute ``rapid growth from tax reductions,'' then what are we to make of 2.3 per cent growth from Mr. Clinton's higher tax rates?
<P>
When it comes to ``disincentives for individuals to work,'' look at what the Economic Report itself says: ``The increase in the overall labor-force-participation rate has slowed since the late 1980s. . . . The stagnant participation rate has been one of the more enduring aspects of this expansion.'' Many secondary earners, mostly women, dropped out of the job market after the counterproductive, revenue-losing tax-rate increases of 1990 and 1993. The percentage of families with two or more earners, for example, dropped to 56.4 per cent in 1993 from 58.2 per cent in 1989, while the percentage with zero workers rose. This should come as no surprise. Assuming the first earner makes more than $140,000, the very first dollar of a second earner's income is now taxed at the same demoralizing 36 - 40 per cent rate as the first earner's last dollar.
<P>
More and more people are also retiring earlier. This too was quite predictable. The extra 1993 tax on Social Security benefits severely punishes older people who keep working, or who made the mistake of having saved enough to afford a modest retirement. The increase in the already punitive estate tax also undermines a major incentive for working and saving in later years.
<P>
In 1993, the earned-income tax credit increased the share of the loot given to those with incomes well above the poverty level. That too discouraged additional work and additional workers. Marginal tax rates on any extra income are now 50 - 75 per cent for two-thirds of EITC recipients.
<P>
The reduction in the supply of willing workers is what kept the measured unemployment rate low, despite the fact that employment has grown by only 1.3 per cent a year since 1991, down from 2.4 per cent in 1983 - 89. Labor Department demographers had forecast that the labor force would grow by 1.3 per cent a year in the 1990s, but it has not even grown by 1 per cent. If the number of job seekers had grown as rapidly as the demographic experts suggested, there would be a lot more people looking for work, and the unemployment rate would now be well above 8 per cent. If the labor force had grown as rapidly as in the Eighties, the unemployment rate would exceed 11 per cent.
<P>
What about ``disincentives . . . to save''? Since tax rates went up in 1993, personal saving has dropped to 4.2 per cent of after-tax income, down from 5.9 per cent in 1992. Measured in constant 1992 dollars, real personal saving was only $223.8 billion in 1995, compared with $310.5 billion ten years earlier. Increased tax rates on high-income individuals and on corporations directly reduced the amount of disposable income left to save, as well as reducing incentives to save.
<P>
Apologists for Clinton's economic policies often blame Alan Greenspan for the sluggish growth of output and income. Has the Fed been discouraging growth through excessively tight monetary policy? Hardly. Short-term interest rates have been much lower in the past three years than they ever were in 1983 - 89, in both nominal and real terms. In other words, the Fed was less accommodating in the 1980s than today, but we had higher growth then.
<P>
By the time of the November election, living standards will have gone nowhere but down for seven years. This is unprecedented. In the 49 years that figures on median family income have been collected, they never before declined for seven years. The worst economic performance in fifty years, as Mr. Clinton used to say, is arguably right now.




<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
