<HTML>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<TITLE>The Real Clinton</TITLE>
<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/real2.gif" ALT="The Real Clinton">
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->


<HR  width=50%>
<H1>Apparatchik Land</H1>
<p>

<p>
<H3>RICH LOWRY</H3>  
<P>
<HR  width=50>Mr. Lowry is NR's national political reporter.
<BR>
<HR  width=50%>
</CENTER>
<P>



<FONT SIZE=+3>O</FONT><font size=+1>N</font> June 22, 1994, Secretary of Labor Robert Reich, to no fanfare whatsoever, issued Interpretative Bulletin 94-1 (IB 94-1). The bulletin applied to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA), a 1974 law designed to protect pension funds from reckless managers. Section 404 of the law makes creating benefits for pension beneficiaries the ``exclusive purpose'' of pension investing. This is the part of ERISA that Reich's bulletin re-interpreted, saying pension-fund managers could consider both the interests of beneficiaries and secondary benefits to other parties when investing pension funds. A hard-to-follow exercise in bureaucratic minutiae? Well, yes. Insignificant? No. Interpretative Bulletin 94-1 was an opening shot in a Clinton Administration policy offensive potentially as radical in scope as its health-care plan, an attempt to tap into a portion of the nation's $3.5 trillion in private pension-money funds to advance its social agenda.
<P>
The re-interpretation of ERISA, and the supporting efforts surrounding it, exemplify the way the Clinton Administration has tweaked regulations and interpretations of law to make policy advances; the way its mid-level personnel has agitated for an agenda at odds with the Administration's public, centrist pose; and the cozy relationship between the Clinton Executive Branch and the activist Left. The Executive Branch and the larger federal bureaucracy by themselves -- without grandiose legislative proposals or high-profile public advocacy -- provide endless opportunities for prosecuting an ideological agenda and protecting the cold political interests of a President. This most political Administration has taken every opportunity afforded it, prospering in Washington's legal and bureaucratic thickets.
<P>
The Clinton Administration re-interpreted ERISA so as to clear the way for so-called Economically Targeted Investments (ETIs). A long-time favorite of the Left, the thrust of ETIs is to steer private pension funds to public purposes (investments in public housing, infrastructure projects, jobs programs, etc.). For the Left, ETIs are a handy way to control middle-class dollars -- diverting retirement funds from more profitable uses -- without an actual tax increase. Clinton, who promoted ETIs in Arkansas, included in his 1992 policy manifesto ``Putting People First'' a proposal for $80 billion of federal investment in social projects to be leveraged with public and private pensions. Once he took office, his Administration began to push the ETI agenda, beneath headlines and the notice of much of the public.
<P>
Assistant Labor Secretary Olena Berg banged the drums across the country for ETIs. A former board member of the California Public Employees Retirement System, which had already gone in big for social investments, she boasted that ``This is the beginning of a turning point.'' In February of 1994 she urged big investors, according to <I>Business Week</I>, ``to invest the dollars now held by pension funds in ways that create more jobs.'' HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros, meanwhile, was setting up what he called a ``precedent-setting initiative to attract pension-fund investments to housing for low-income people''; six pension funds agreed to invest in affordable housing projects with $100 million in federal backing. After the Administration issued IB94-1 in June of 1994, it also set up a federal ``clearinghouse'' to showcase successful social investments. 
<P>
The pedigree of ETIs -- Miss Berg herself calls them ``a radical notion'' -- has been documented by the Joint Economic Committee (JEC), which has worked aggressively to expose the Clinton offensive on pensions. A moving force behind the idea is the Center for Policy Alternatives (CPA), a socialistic spin-off of the radical Institute for Policy Studies. CPA has flacked tirelessly for ETIs at least since 1990. In the Clinton Administration, it finally had a sympathetic ear. A CPA conference on the idea in 1995 drew some half-dozen Administration participants. CPA's ``public capital program'' manager tells of working closely with Administration officials on ETIs. Indeed, the idea of a clearinghouse had been proposed by CPA, and the Administration initially even selected the organization as the contractor for the project.
<P>
All this has effectively been shut down by Rep. Jim Saxton (R., N.J.), vice chairman of the JEC, who sponsored a bill that passed by a wide margin, repealing Reich's IB 94-1 and abolishing the clearinghouse. The pension issue is a natural for the GOP, and Democrats sense it. But the feckless Sen. Nancy Kassebaum has sat on a companion bill in the Senate. Which is par for the course: the Administration pushing to the limits on behalf of its agenda, while Republicans pull up short on the counterattack. ``They're chillingly pragmatic about all this, realizing that they can't advance the liberal parts of their agenda publicly so they find imaginative ways to try to do it anyway,'' says one House aide. There have been a number of underground ways the Administration has continued a liberal march without much attention, manipulating the bureaucracy and advancing its agenda by stealth. If declaring the end of ``the era of big government'' is the Clinton Administration by day, this is it by night.
<P>
Take RU-486. Abortion is one of the issues on which Clinton can't leave the Left -- despite the ``rare'' rhetoric -- so he was eager to deliver on the ``abortion pill.'' In January of 1993 Clinton wrote HHS Secretary Donna Shalala -- FDA Commissioner David Kessler's boss -- a memo asking HHS to promote the ``testing, licensing, and manufacturing'' of the drug. Kessler had pre-emptively reacted to the pressure five weeks after the 1992 elections, unilaterally reversing Bush Administration policy. He wrote to RU-486's manufacturer, Roussel Uclaf, prodding it to apply for approval in the U.S. (``further clinical trials may not be required,'' he added helpfully). Everybody all around got the hints -- Kessler doing Clinton's bidding to save his job, Roussel Uclaf doing Kessler's bidding to avoid future run-ins. RU-486 is slated for FDA approval as early as September, and the Clinton Administration will have provided America with the drug as surely as if it had sponsored legislation to do so. 
<P>
<font size=+3>F</font><font size=+1>EDERAL</font> departments, meanwhile, have become touchstones for the organized Left and agents for advancing a PC agenda otherwise seen only on college campuses. The EPA, for instance, is a breeding ground for self-perpetuating activism. Since 1993, according to a GAO report, grants awarded for workshops, conferences, and non-scientific studies -- mostly the province of environmental advocacy groups -- have nearly doubled, from roughly $130 million to about $250 million. The American Association of Retired Persons has received some $40 million in 23 different grants since 1993; the Environmental Defense Fund has grabbed $1.8 million. Meanwhile, despite an amendment to the Family and Medical Leave Act introduced by Sen. Don Nickles (R., Okla.) stipulating that it wouldn't apply to domestic partners, the EPA includes domestic partners in its own leave plan. EPA chief Carol Browner proudly cited the policy in an e-mail celebrating June as Gay and Lesbian Pride Month -- ``In Headquarters, and in some Regional Offices, activities are being organized by the Chapters of the Gay, Lesbian, or Bisexual Employees (GLOBE) of EPA. Please join them . . .''
<P>
More broadly, the Administration has made full use of the propaganda power of the executive branch (see Christina Hoff Sommers, next page). The Civil Service subcommittee of the House Reform and Oversight Committee under Rep. John Mica (R., Fla.) has documented an Administration effort to ``roll out'' a weekly message through the public-affairs offices of federal departments, including those in field offices nationwide. (Veterans Affairs, Labor, and the EPA seem to be heavily involved.) ``It's putting hundreds of government employees at work flacking for you all over the country,'' says a House aide. House Reform and Oversight Committee Chairman Bill Clinger (R., Penn.) conducted a May hearing on the Administration's wide-ranging politicization of the federal bureaucracy: 
<P>
<blockquote>
 -- VA Secretary Jesse Brown included a long ``message'' on employees' check stubs. ``As I have been telling the nation's veterans organizations this summer,'' Brown wrote, ``the Administration's [budget] plan is much better for veterans and their families.''
<P>
 -- In February 1995 an internal EPA e-mail discussed how ``Enviros are looking for some help in the conference committee on unfunded mandates,'' and suggested what the agency could do to support their lobbying. 
<P>
 -- A state director of the Department of the Interior's Bureau of Land Management wrote a letter last year advising public-land constituents of the department's opposition to a GOP grazing bill and inviting them ``to come together to work for the health of the public lands and the long-term economic stability of the West.'' Cabinet Secretaries can certainly take positions on public issues, but their departments aren't supposed to be arms of a permanent political campaign.</blockquote> 
<P>
Unions have been an integral part of this campaign too. Federal public-employee unions were kept apprised of crucial early strategy meetings organized by the Treasury Department to prepare for the looming budget crisis in 1995 (the meetings, again, were uncovered by Saxton's Joint Economic Committee). Ordinarily, public-employee unions would be concerned about a government shutdown and Treasury's planned raid on their pension trust funds during it. Instead, the unions eagerly participated in the Administration's shut-down strategy. ``We will be '<B>ON THEIR CASE AND IN THEIR FACE</B>,''' the American Federation of Government Employees president wrote of GOP freshmen in an August 1995 letter to members, well in advance of any shutdown. ``The question is not whether we work, but in what kind of America we will work.'' The Administration has paid back the unions for their loyalty. The Office of Personnel Management provided names and home addresses of its employees -- a clear breach of their privacy -- to the unions representing them. Mica's subcommittee discovered an OMB letter confirming that other federal agencies would be doing the same. 
<P>
There is a certain virtuosity to all this. The Democrats simply are more comfortable with power than the Republicans. That's why the Clinton Administration can -- after some initial stumbles -- push and pull all the political levers like an expert lathe operator. Two other factors are at work as well. One is necessity. The political imperative in the current environment is to move, as Ralph Reed once famously said of the Christian Coalition, ``quietly, with stealth, under cover of night.'' The other is lack of scruple. The Administration reflects the Clintons' ruthlessness in pursuit of power. The theme of former Republican officials brought to Capitol Hill to testify on Clinton Administration practices is always: We never would have done that, we couldn't have gotten away with it. Well, for whatever reason, the Clinton Administration can. For Republicans, the reward for their virtue is in heaven. The reward for the Clintonites' shamelessness may well be in a second term.

