</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<TITLE>The Real Clinton</TITLE>
<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/real2.gif" ALT="The Real Clinton">
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->


<HR  width=50%>
<H1>New Girls' Network</H1>
<p>

<p>
<H3>SAMUEL DEALEY</H3>  
<P>
<HR  width=50>Mr. Dealey is based at NR's Washington office.
<BR>
<HR  width=50%>
</CENTER>
<P>



<FONT SIZE=+3>F</FONT><font size=+1>OUNDED</font> in 1989, Ervin and Associates, a contracting firm based in Bethesda, Md., and specializing in affordable housing, more than tripled in size in its first five years. In July, 1994 its work was commended by Assistant Secretary for Housing Nicholas Retsinas in testimony before the House Subcommittee on Employment, Housing, and Aviation. Following the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995, the company raised over $165,000 to help the families of HUD employees who lost their lives. On John Ervin's office wall hangs a framed picture of his staff with HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros to mark the occasion, and a letter from the Secretary notes, ``The HUD family will always be grateful for your kindness.''
<P>
Well, maybe not ``always.'' Ervin has filed a suit against the department claiming its rampant politicization is running him out of business. Specifically, Ervin charges that the head of HUD's housing division, Helen Dunlap, has steered lucrative federal contract awards -- known by industry types as ``honey pots'' -- to her ``contractors of choice,'' in keeping with her animus against white males. Since Miss Dunlap's political appointment in 1994, Mr. Ervin's federal contacts have been cut almost in half, and the firm has had to downsize its full-time staff from 47 to 23. Moreover, Ervin claims, HUD's employment practice reflects an institutional bias. HUD counters that Ervin is a ``disgruntled contractor'' and that safeguards prevent contract patronage. His suit is pending in D.C.'s district court, but briefs filed by Ervin and documents he has obtained from HUD highlight disturbing practices -- blatant hiring quotas, outright hostility to white males, and possibly favoritism in contracts -- that go unnoticed in the thicket of the federal bureaucracy. 
<P>
Mr. Ervin asserts he has been recommended for many contracts by so-called source evaluation boards -- panels of career civil servants that are meant to combat patronage -- only to see Helen Dunlap ``orchestrate'' efforts to ``bypass the normal procurement processes which are intended to prevent the very abuses'' Ervin is being subjected to. In one case, Ervin alleges Miss Dunlap awarded a $30-million asset-management contract to the purportedly ``disadvantaged'' firm Williams and Adley, breaching a prior contract which Ervin says HUD previously informed him was legally his. Following objections raised by Ervin and career housing-division employees, according to <I>Housing Affairs Letter</I>, the HUD inspector general launched an investigation into contract malfeasance by the housing division. Miss Dunlap was demoted from her political appointment as Deputy Assistant Secretary for Multifamily Housing to Deputy Assistant Secretary for Housing Operations.
<P>
Despite this, Helen Dunlap reportedly waged a power struggle with her replacement (a white male), holding duplicate staff meetings immediately after his and asserting that she was still in charge and didn't intend to surrender. And she apparently won; she inexplicably regained her jurisdiction over contract awards and, Mr. Ervin claims, vindictively blackballs his firm from obtaining such awards. ``They throw the fox out of the hen house and then let it back in,'' says Ervin.
<P>
This attitude carries over into the way Miss Dunlap manages her division. <I>Housing Affairs Letter</I> quotes one high-level HUD source who says Dunlap ``made many enemies after joining the department.'' According to anonymous moles in HUD, she refers to the men in her front office as ``TOMs,'' or ``Tired Old Males,'' and has said that ``the only fitting position for a male is a secretary.'' It is not without reason that some of these career employees have been known to call their office a ``white boys' hell.''
<P>
But discrimination is not confined to Helen Dunlap and HUD contracts. Department managers are ranked on how well they achieve cultural diversity within their divisions. They are given evaluations with ratings of Outstanding, Fully Successful, and Unacceptable; an ``outstanding'' manager ``takes actions and makes decisions regarding hiring, promotions, training, upward mobility, recommendations for selection, and other personnel or administrative matters that further the Department's . . . Affirmative Employment Program policies and foster diversity within the HUD workplace.'' In short, color over merit.
<P>
Internal hiring data obtained by John Ervin under the Freedom of Information Act indicate what close attention is paid to ``diversity.'' A chart produced by HUD breaks down each department division by race and gender, noting changes over a six-month cycle. From September 1995 to March 1996, for example, Miss Dunlap's Office of Housing severely cut white men from the better professional and administrative positions (professionals down 10 per cent compared to 1 per cent department-wide).
<P>
In a previous analysis by HUD for 1996, the department reported a ``manifest imbalance'' (representation ``substantially below'' the civilian labor force) within its housing division in professional Hispanic females, and administrative and technical white females. An accompanying chart entitled ``Internal Movement Numerical Objectives'' called for 90 ``planned'' division hirings -- 20 white females, 20 black females, 20 black males, 10 Hispanic males, 10 Hispanic females, 5 Asian males, and 5 Asian females. Figures for white males were nil.
<P>
What is most striking, however, is not that HUD uses quotas in its hiring and promotions, but that the basis for these quotas in divisions across the country appears to be the Civilian Labor Force statistics for Washington, D.C. That is, a district field office in, say, Kansas City must strive to reflect the demographic composition of D.C. workers (the city's population is over 70 per cent minority). Kansas City's HUD field office has a total of five employees at the professional level: three white males, two black males. In a HUD document titled ``Assessment of Underrepresentation,'' the department categorizes all employees by race and gender and suggests in a ``number needed'' column that Kansas City should hire two white women, two black women, and a male and female each of Hispanic, Asian, and American Indian derivation.
<P>
Interestingly, in every assessment of white-male underrepresentation spanning HUD's 10 regions and 79 field offices, there is no ``number needed'' advisement for more white males.
<P>
While Nelson Diaz, head of HUD's office of General Counsel, mandates an obligatory three-and-a-half hour ``sensitivity training'' seminar for his employees, he apparently could use a little of this himself. According to attendees at a September 22, 1993, meeting of field counsel, Mr. Diaz declared that there are ``too many white faces at HUD.'' Subsequently, attempts were made to remove John Dellera (who is white) as Assistant General Counsel for New York/New Jersey. ``I doubted that the reassignment was bona fide and suspected it was an unlawful attempt to coerce my resignation so that Nelson could appoint some political friend to the job,'' Dellera wrote friends. Diaz replaced Dellera with a female Hispanic -- the office was deficient in the Hispanic female professional category, according to HUD reports. 
<P>
If the department isn't violating the letter of the law after the Supreme Court's <I>Adarand</I> decision -- which held that race preferences will receive ``the strictest judicial scrutiny'' and will ``seldom provide a relevant basis for disparate treatment'' -- it certainly violates the spirit. Not that it seems to matter. A May 16, 1996 HUD report dismisses the decision: ``<I>Adarand</I> did not provide clear judicial precedent on the constitutionality of specific affirmative action/ set-aside programs.'' Until the Supreme Court more clearly defines its guidelines, John Ervin just hopes to stay in the black -- despite being a white male trying to do business with Helen Dunlap's HUD.

<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
