<head><title>JUNE 26, 1995 VOL. XLVII, NO. 12 -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>


<CENTER><H2>JUNE 26, 1995 VOL. XLVII, NO. 12</CENTER></H2>
<HR>
<H3>Cover Story</H3>

<P><B>Presidential Politics</B>
Since approval demands perfection, NATIONAL REVIEW unveils (p. 16) the ideal presidential candidate. . . . Richard Brookhiser (p. 27) explores the mysterious Gramm campaign. . . . Kate  O'Beirne (p. 45) says the Catholic voting block is available. . . . Wm. F. Buckley Jr. (p. 70) looks at Lamar Alexander's bottom line.
<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>Articles</H3>

<P><B>25 <A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/gramm.html">On the Scene</A></B>
Peter W. Rodman untangles the Clinton Administration's Bosnia policy. . . . Robin Harris gets the local word out of Europe. . . . Anthony Daniels decries the carnage in Chechnya. . . . Matthew Scully witnesses the installation of Spiro Agnew's Capitol bust.

<B><P>31 Does Constitutional Law Exist?</B>
Lino A. Graglia explains how the rule of law has been replaced by the rule of judges, and interprets the latest Supreme Court legislation in Lopez and Thornton.

<B><P>43 Republicans Against the Revolution</B>
Rich Lowry fingers GOP congressmen who are protecting their own special interests against conservative reform.

<P><B>47 Case of the Falling Sperm Counts</B>
John Berlau puts pseudo-science under the microscope, and examines the tactics behind media health scares.

<P><B>48 Cleaning Up Superfund</B>
Richard Miniter outlines steps to reform Superfund.

<P><B>50 Death, Be Not Proud</B>
Robert P. George and William C. Porth Jr.  take on Ernest van den Haag's arguments for suicide in round two of our debate.
<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>Special Section</H3>

<P><B>36 Gekko Balances the Budget</B>
Stephen Moore and Daniel J. Mitchell examine Republican budgets and find them fair, but only fair. . . . Ben Zycher recommends more spending cuts, and more tax cuts. . . . Spencer Abraham defends the abolition of Federal departments. . . . Linda Bridges considers alternatives to the Welfare State.
<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>Books, Arts & Manners</H3>

<P><B>56 Can Christianity save black America, as Alan Keyes and Glenn Loury suggest in Masters of the Dream and One by One from the Inside Out?</B>
 John J. DiIulio Jr. says Amen. . . . Alan Ryan's John Dewey and the High Tide of American Liberalism has the faults of its subjects, reports John Gray. . . . James Bowman thinks Anne Tyler is a little too cute in Ladder of Years. . . . Hadley Arkes recalls Leo Strauss, worshipper at the Temple of Reason. . . . John Simon wishes he could Forget Paris, and checks into Hotel Sorrento. . . . At Richard Brookhiser's gym, bodybuilders pump iron -- politely.

<P><B>72 <A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/misanthr.html"> The Misanthrope's
Corner</A></B>
Florence King focuses like a laser beam on America's shrinking attention span.
<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=LEFT>
<H3>Sections</H3>

<P> 4 Letters<BR>
6 From the Editor<BR>
8 For the Record<BR>
10 <A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/theweek.html">The Week</A><BR>
53 <A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/gore.html">Letter from Al</A><BR>
54 Help<BR>
66 Books in Brief<BR>
69 Trans-O-Gram<BR>
70 On the Right<BR>

