<html>
<head>
<title>Economic Effects From Universal, Unlimited IRAs</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1><center>The Economic Effects Of Legislation Enacting
Universal, Unlimited, Tax-Deductible IRAs</center></h1>
<p>
<pre>

			Increase in GDP			Additional Jobs
	Year		(In $ Billions)		 	 (In Thousands)
        ----            ---------------			---------------

	1996			  153				  489
	2000			  418				1,182
	2010			1,090				1,936
	2020			2,158				2,377
	2030			4,246				2,897
	2040			8,352				3,532
	2060		       32,318				5,078
</pre>
The GDP (Gross Domestic Product) figures represent the change in nominal 
GDP relative to the baseline for that year.  For example, GDP will be 
$2.2 trillion higher in the year 2020 than it would otherwise be in the 
adsence of universal IRAs.  And, by the year 2020, there will be 2.4 
million more jobs in that year than in the absence of universal IRAs.  By 
the year 2060, the increase in GDP from universal, unlimited, 
tax-deductible IRAs will be $32 trillion in excess of GDP otherwise 
available, and 5 million more jobs will be created than otherwise 
available.<br>
<p>
The estimated economic effects illustrated in the above table assume that 
the assets held within universal IRA-type accounts without any penalty 
tax on distribution would have a maximum holding period of just five 
years, and that each contribution would be uniformly withdrawn over five 
years.  In other words, on average, each dollar contributed to the IRA 
would be withdrawn at a rate of 20% per year. (<i>The maximum assumed 
holding period of five years indicates a weighted average holding 
period of 2 1/2 years.  It is the League's view that over a period 
of time such a weighted average holding period will be low and thus 
the assumption is quite conservative.</i>)<br> 
<p>
Since the duration of the average holding period is a determinant of 
gains to be derived from universal IRAs, a sensitivity test indicates 
that if the five-year assumed holding period was increased or decreased 
by just one year, the aggregate IRA assets would be increased by 15%-20% 
within ten years.  It is estimated that adding just one year to the 
assumed holding period would ultimately reduce the effective personal 
income tax rate on savings by 60%.<br>
<p>
<h3><i>Clearly, it is in the interests of everyone, including the 
government, to encourage maximum tax-deductible IRA saving to be held for 
the longest duration possible.</i></h3><br>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b>  The above table was taken from a study commissioned by the 
Savers &amp; 
Investors League by the respected consulting firm of Fiscal Associates, 
Inc..  In that study, they addressed the future dynamic gains to be 
derived from the enactment of universal, unlimited, tax-deductible IRA-type 
legislation.  The study was completed in 1993 and all subsequent yearly 
figures were calculated assuming the enacted legislation would have 
occurred in 1993.<br>
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>][<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>]<br>
<font size=1>Savers &amp; Investors League, 1996</font><br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
