<DOCNO>WT26-B32-169</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA029-000308-B033-103</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.mediaresearch.org:80/savers/library/tabgain.html 204.71.237.92 19970114132537 text/html 2605
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 13:25:57 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Mar-96 17:47:32 GMT
Content-length: 2419
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Estimated Revenue Gains and Losses From Universal IRAs</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1><center>Estimated Static Revenue Losses And Dynamic Revenue Gains 
From Universal, Unlimited, Tax-Deductibe IRAs</center></h1> 
<p>
<h3><center>BILLIONS OF DOLLARS</center></h3><br>
<p>
<pre>
                                                        Net Present-Value
		     Static		Dynamic		     of GDP
	Years	  Revenue (Loss)    Revenue Gains      (Discounted @ 11.6%)
	-----	  --------------    -------------      --------------------

	1996	    $    (36)	      $     27		   $      231
	2000		 (67)		    69			  916
	2010		(146)		   178 			2,830
	2020		(288)		   370			4,186
	2030		(567)		   762			5,076
	2040	      (1,115)		 1,571			5,661
	2060	      (4,314)	  	 6,677			6,297		
</pre>
<p>
The above estimates of the governments's static revenue estimates for 
universal IRAs show a substantial loss in federal revenue.  However, the
estimates also indicate that the dynamic economic results flowing from 
universal IRAs will create sufficient added tax revenues to more than 
offset the static losses.  For example, in the year 2000, the extra tax 
revenue from the expanded, dynamic economic growth will more than offset 
the $67 billion in forgone ordinary income taxes.  With the gap growing 
each year, by the year 2060, the net dynamic federal tax revenue gain in 
excess of static revenue loss from the ordinary income tax will be in 
excess of $2.3 trillion.<br>
<p>
Forecasting the GDP growth for the next sixty five years, it is estimated 
that the net present-value of our nation's GDP to be derived from 
universal, unlimited, tax-deductible IRAs is almost $6.3 trillion dollars 
greater than it would be in the absence of this legislation.<br>

<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b>  The above table was taken from a study commissioned by the 
Savers &amp; 
Investors League by the respected consulting firm of Fiscal Associates, 
Inc..  In that study, they addressed the future dynamic gains to be 
derived from the enactment of universal, unlimited, tax-deductible 
IRA-type legislation.  The study was completed in 1993 and all subsequent 
yearly figures were calculated assuming the enacted legislation would 
have occurred in 1993.<br>
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>][<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>]<br>
<font size=1>Savers &amp; Investors League, 1996</font><br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
