<HEAD>
<title>League News - 12/15/94</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">
<center>
<img src = "/savers/images/griffgrn.gif">
<br>
<img src="/savers/images/news2.gif"></strong><br>
<p>
<font size=4>NEW CONGRESS: IT'S THE ECONOMY, STUPID </font></center>
<p>
Washington, D.C., December 15, 1994 - Our nation is in a &quot;saving&quot;  crisis. 
This crisis is self-inflicted due to the erroneous way our government measures
alleged tax revenue loss from tax-deferred plans like IRAs. 
<p>
In short, the government treats IRA tax deferrals as an expense, when in reality,
the tax deferrals, by their very nature, are government assets.  Certainly, every
IRA owner recognizes that he or she has a tax liability if and when an IRA
withdrawal is ma de.  It's obvious that when the taxpayer has a liability to the
government, the government has an asset of like amount.  That's not and expense! 

Does this governmental error make a difference?  Absolutely-and the cost to
taxpayers, our nation, our economy, and to the government's tax collections, is
mind boggling high! 

The respected economic advisory firm, Fiscal Associates, prepared an analysis that
measured the future fiscal effects of legislation that allows any person to have
unlimited tax deductions for any IRA contributions.  See Table 1. </PRE>

<center><H3>Table 1</H3>

Estimated Static Revenue Losses and Dynamic Revenue Gains</br>
From Universal, Unlimited, Tax-Deductible IRAs
<P>

<H3>BILLIONS OF DOLLARS</H3></center>

<PRE>
                                                      Net Present-Values
                                                      Of Gains (Losses)
                                      Net Dynamic     Discounted @ 11.6%*
          Static         Dynamic      Federal Tax     Net Dynamic
Years   Review(Loss)  Review Gains  Gains & (Losses)  Tax Revenue    GDP
<hr>
           (a)            (b)            (c)              (d)         (e)

1995     $   (28)      $    18       $   (10)         $   (23)     $  121
2000         (67)           69             2              (31)        916
2010        (146)          178            32               11        2830
2020        (288)          370            82               57        4186
2030        (567)          762           195               95        5076
2040       (1115)         1571           456              124        5661
2060       (4314)         6677          2363              164        6297
<hr></pre>   
<h6> *The net present-value calculations
assume a discount rate of 11.6 percent-the estimated rate of return to society
given by a long-term return on mutual funds.  This study was prepared in 1993 and
published in Wealth Is Not A Dirty Word, Mill Run Press, P aoli, PA.  The swing
(i.e., loss to gain) in estimated revenues (b-a) is mind boggling (e.g., $136
billion in year 2000)! 
</h6>
The government measures tax revenue on the unrealistic &quot;static&quot; basis
shown above, i.e., the government assumes people don't change their actions when
tax laws are changed, and ignores expanded tax collections from a soundly growing
economy.  [R emember how a static estimate raised taxes on boats, thereby killing
hobs and losing tax revenue?] The &quot;dynamic&quot; basis reflects the realistic
fact that people respond to tax law changes.  In this case, new net saving will
grow dramatically. 
<p>
Increased saving, created by unlimited, tax-deductible IRAs would increase
production, increase jobs, reduce interest costs, and increase tax revenue. 
Taxpayers after-tax income (and related standard of living) by the year 
2000 would be increased as shown in Table 2. </PRE>
<p>
<center><H3>Table 2</H3>
<p>

How Universal, Unlimited, Tax-Deductible IRAs<br>
Will Increase After-Tax Incomes In the Year 2000</center>
<p>
<pre>
                 Adjusted Gross               Percent Change In
                    Income                     After Tax Income
<hr>  
                 Under $5000                         .2%
                 $5000-$10000                       3.4%
                 10000-20000                       13.6%
                 20000-30000                       19.3%
                 30000-40000                       12.4%
                 40000-50000                       12.3%
                 50000-100000                      23.3%
                 100000-200000                      6.3%
                 200000-500000                      3.3%
                 500000 or more                     5.8%                                                

<center><h6>*Adjusted gross income as currently defined</h6></center>
</pre>
Clearly, Congress must immediately put a stop using the thoroughly discredited
static &quot;tax expenditure&quot; method for estimation tax revenues from
tax-deferred plans such as IRAs.  The static method directs governmental tax policy
180 degrees in th e wrong direction.  Without changing any other provision of the
law, correctly measuring the tax impact of unlimited, tax-deductible IRAs would
swiftly increase the after-tax income of middle America by 12% to 20%! 
<p>

On November 8th, the American people voted for rational, substantive change, not
just slogans.  There's no sounder change than H.R. 3179 and S. 929 (103rd
Congress).  These identical bills achieve the desired results portrayed above and
will be reintroduc ed in the 104th Congress. 
<p>

Every caring American should write his or her Representative and Senators now and
urge immediate enactment.  There is no reason for delay.  Every day of delay makes
matters worse. 
<P>
